fail threshold, the fallback picks from all scored candidates (including \"GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\"). \n\nThe fallback sorts by position, so position 0 comes first. \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" is at position 0. UNLESS the 2-line join \"Smażona zielona fasolka GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\" also has position 0 (same position as the first line of the join), and it has higher score. But sort is `a.position - b.position || b.score - a.score`, so same position → higher score wins. If the join has higher score than the single, the join would be selected.\n\nBut then the result would be \"Smażona zielona fasolka GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\", not empty. I keep tracing paths that don't lead to an empty string. Let me step back—maybe all lines are actually failing the hard filters, which would leave candidates empty. But checking the lines again, both \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" and \"GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\" pass. So that's not it either. Maybe the issue is that the function itself is throwing an exception, which the test catches and returns empty, or maybe I'm analyzing the wrong part of the code entirely. about what is MOST LIKELY happening:\n\nGiven the file structure:\n- Line 1: \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" (Polish title, mixed case)\n- Line 2: \"GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\" (English translation, ALL_CAPS)\n- Line 3: \"그린빈 볶음\" (Korean translation)\n\nThe most likely failure is in the bilingual detection / multi-title guard interaction:\n\n1. The bilingual detection DOES identify \"GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\" as a translation of \"Smażona zielona fasolka\"\n2. \"GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\" is removed from scoredForThreshold\n3. BUT: the 2-line join \"Smażona zielona fasolka GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\" is NOT removed (it doesn't start with the translation text)\n4. This join likely has stronger embedding similarity because it includes English food terms, so it dominates scoredForThreshold\n5. If both the single Polish title and the joined version pass the threshold, dedup would remove the longer one and keep just \"Sma