having no candidates to begin with. Let me check whether every candidate could actually fail those initial filters.\n\nLooking at \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" specifically, I'm testing it against the garbling check by stripping out non-ASCII letters like the Polish ż character, which leaves me with roughly 20 letters across the three words. That should pass the garbling threshold. Now I'm finishing the vowel count for \"zielona\" and \"fasolka\", getting 4 and 3 vowels respectively, which totals 10 vowels across 20 letters—a ratio of 0.5 that passes the vowel threshold. Then I'm checking the multi-word garble validation, starting with \"Smażona\" which fails the lowercase check since it starts with uppercase S, while \"zielona\" passes and I'm about to filter out non-alphabetic characters from it. ona fasolka GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\" mixes both title and translation and stays in scoredForThreshold. If the Korean line somehow interferes or if the join dominates, the result might be wrong or empty.\n\nLet me trace through the ALL_CAPS coalescing logic one more time. Starting from burstEnd=0, the first item \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" isn't all caps so it gets pushed directly. The second item \"GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\" is all caps with 3 words, which exceeds the threshold of 2, so it also gets pushed as-is. The Korean text at index 2 would follow the same pattern.\n\nMoving through the rest of the items, most aren't all caps and get pushed directly. When I hit \"DLA & OSOB\", it's technically all caps but again has 3 words, so it doesn't meet the coalescing condition and gets pushed. The remaining items like \"Przvgetowanie\", \"15 minut\", and \"Smazenie 15 minut\" all get pushed without any special handling.\n\nNow at \"SKLADNIKI\" - this is all caps and a single word, which would normally trigger caps coalescence. But I need to check what comes next to see if there are more all-caps lines to merge together, so I'm looking at the subsequent lines to determine if this should