REENBEANSBORKEUMK\" wait: \"GREEN BEANS BORKEUM 그린빈 볶음\" → letters = \"GREENBEANSBORKEUMRK\" hmm let me not count Korean. letters = \"GREENBEANSBORKEUM\" = 17 letters. Vowels: E,E,E,A,O,E,U = 7. ratio = 7/17 ≈ 0.41 ✓. No garbled words (all caps). passesHardFilters passes.\n  - So \"GREEN BEANS BORKEUM 그린빈 볶음\" added as 2-line candidate!\n\nInteresting! The Korean characters go along for the ride in multi-line joins.\n\nNow in the bilingual detection, I'm looking for the first non-all-caps candidate at position 0, which is \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" since it comes before the 2-line join in the candidates list. Then I'm filtering for all-caps entries at positions 1-2 that came from single-line candidates, starting with \"GREEN\".\n\nFor the layout-based method, I'm extracting words longer than 2 characters from the position 0 entry and comparing them against the all-caps candidate—there's no overlap between the Polish words and the English ones, and the all-caps entry has enough words to qualify as a translation candidate.\n\nNow I'm filtering through the scored candidates, removing \"GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\" and any entries that start with it when lowercased. This eliminates both the standalone English phrase and the combined entries that include it, leaving only the Polish text alone and the Polish text paired with the English phrase.\n\nBut here's the critical realization: the structural heading check happens on the raw scored candidates before the bilingual filtering kicks in, so \"GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\" would actually qualify as a structural heading and receive that bonus score. bilingual detection. Let me re-read the scoring logic more carefully.\n\nIn the first pass, I'm computing raw scores for all candidates. Then I identify structural headings and select a base heading based on embedding quality. In the second pass, I apply bonuses like position factor, all-caps bonus, and structural bonus.\n\nSo \"GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\" gets both the all-caps bonus (0.08) and structural bonus (0.10) applied to its final score. The threshold score only includes the raw score plus all-caps bonus, which is why it gets filtered out of the threshold pool. But its full score with all bonuses stays in the main scored array.\n\nThe fallback logic kicks in when nothing passes the threshold—it falls back to the highest-scoring candidate from the full scored array, which would include \"GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\" with its bonuses applied. I'm wondering if the real issue is that all candidates from this file are failing the hard filters, which would explain why nothing makes it through to the final result.\n\nLet me trace through the `isLikelyGarbled` check for \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" more carefully. The lowercase letter check at the start should pass since \"S\" is uppercase. And there's no period followed by a space and letter in the title, so that filter shouldn't catch it either.\n\nI can't pinpoint the exact bug without actually running the code, so I'll write up the analysis focusing on the structural issues: the trilingual layout, how bilingual detection removes \"GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\" as a candidate but the structural heading bonus was already assigned to it in the scoring phase, and how this misallocation in the empty-pool fallback could cause the Polish title to be underscored relative to the English one.\n\nWait, let me reconsider—what if the problem is simpler than I thought? If `selected` has items but still produces the wrong result, the fallback never triggers. The real question is whether \"GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\" somehow ends up in `selected` despite bilingual detection removing it from `scoredForThreshold`, since `selected` is filtered from that same array. I need to trace whether `selected` actually comes from `scoredForThreshold`.\n\nLooking at the code, `selected` is definitely filtered from `scoredForThreshold`, which means \"GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\" shouldn't be there. But if `selected` ends up empty because everything falls below threshold, the fallback kicks in and uses the full `scored` array—which includes \"GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\" at position 1. Since the fallback sorts by position, the position 0 candidate comes first, and that's what gets selected and passed through the rest of the pipeline.\n\nThe question is whether that position 0 candidate is the single \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" or the multi-line join that includes \"GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\". If it's the join, deduplication would keep the shorter single version only if it's also in `selected`—but if `selected` only contains the one fallback item, then dedup can't remove anything, and the join would be the final result. I'm trying to figure out if there's a scenario where the result ends up completely empty.\n\nMy best guess is that the Polish text has weak embedding similarity to the title reference, causing all scored candidates to fall below the threshold, and then the fallback mechanism itself returns an empty string or fails to find a valid candidate.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering whether \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" even passes the hard filters in the first place. Let me trace through the metadata pattern checks to see if it's being filtered out before it ever gets scored.\n\nActually, I'm wondering if there's a mismatch between how positions are assigned in `buildCandidates` versus how they're being looked up later—the line indices might not correspond the way I'm expecting. I'm working through the line-by-line parsing of this recipe file, and I notice the ingredients section is split across multiple lines—the green beans description continues from line 10 into line 11, and the smoked bacon similarly spans lines 12-13. I'm trying to figure out why the title extraction might be returning undefined, and I'm considering whether the bilingual detection is interfering with the scoring logic or if there's an edge case in how the embedding scores are being evaluated.\n\nLet me trace through the fallback logic more carefully—if selected ends up