ck uses the full `scored` pool which includes the 2-line join with its structural bonus intact. This would normally select the join at position 0, but if the Polish title isn't in `selected` after dedup, the join survives—which should give me the longer version, not an empty string.\n\nI'm still not seeing a clear path to ''. Let me consider whether `candidates.length === 0` could happen—that would mean all lines failed the hard filters, but \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" should pass those checks.\n\nActually, maybe the pruning at >25 candidates is the issue. The file has about 24 non-empty lines, and with single-line, 2-line, and 3-line joins, I'd get around 57 candidates before filtering. After hard filters probably 10-15 survive, so pruning shouldn't kick in. The simpler explanation might be that the function returns `undefined` because \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" itself has some property that causes it to be filtered out or not selected.\n\nWait, I think I see it now. If all the scored candidates have scores below the 0.08 threshold—maybe because the embedding match is weak for Polish words—then the selected pool becomes empty, triggering the fallback that returns the first positional candidate. But if that first candidate is itself filtered or deduplicated away, the function could end up returning `undefined`.\n\nThe core issue seems to be that the mixed-language joins (Polish title with English/Korean translations) aren't being caught by the bilingual detection, and the structural heading bonus gets misapplied to the wrong part of the text. Together, these might suppress the score of \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" enough that it falls below threshold, and if the fallback mechanism doesn't have a valid candidate to return, that's where the empty string comes from.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":27153,"cache_read_input_tokens":33094,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephem